  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Can I claim HRA during ITR Filing?",
  "response": "Yes, you can claim **House Rent Allowance (HRA)** while filing your **Income Tax Return (ITR)**, provided you meet the eligibility criteria and have the necessary documentation. HRA is a component of your salary that is exempt from tax under certain conditions.\n\n### Eligibility to Claim HRA:\n1. **You must be a salaried individual**: HRA is applicable only to salaried employees.\n2. **You must be paying rent**: You need to be paying rent for the accommodation you are staying in.\n3. **You must not own the house**: If you own the house you are living in, you cannot claim HRA.\n\n### Conditions for HRA Exemption:\nThe exemption is calculated as the **least of the following**:\n1. **Actual HRA received** from your employer.\n2. **Rent paid minus 10% of your salary** (basic + DA).\n3. **50% of salary** (if you live in a metro city: Delhi, Mumbai, Chennai, or Kolkata) or **40% of salary** (for non-metro cities).\n\n### Documents Required:\n- Rent receipts signed by your landlord.\n- Rent agreement (if applicable).\n- PAN of the landlord (if rent exceeds \u20b91 lakh per year).\n\n### How to Claim HRA in ITR:\n1. **Under Salary Income**: HRA exemption is already part of your Form 16, which is issued by your employer.\n2. **While Filing ITR**: You don\u2019t need to manually claim HRA again if your employer has already considered it. However, ensure the correct amount is reflected in your ITR.\n3. **Self-Claiming HRA**: If your employer did not consider HRA exemption, you can calculate and claim it under \"Income from Salary\" while filing your ITR.\n\n### Important Notes:\n- If you\u2019re self-employed or a freelancer, you cannot claim HRA but can claim a deduction for rent paid under **Section 80GG**.\n- Ensure the rent payments are genuine, as false claims can lead to penalties.\n\nAlways cross-verify your HRA claims with the details in Form 16 and maintain proper documentation for rent payments. If you\u2019re unsure, consult a tax advisor for assistance.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
